Ministry's accusation 

Although Wine insists his call is for peaceful protests, Security ministry Elly Tumwine recently said that the Kyadondo East MP and his supporters are using the protest as a scapegoat to cause chaos and violence. 

“They (Bobi Wine) are using the words 'peaceful demonstrations' as a cover-up. Leaflets with hate speech are being dumped and lethal weapons such as knives, machetes have been withdrawn from some protesters," he claimed. 

In his online address on the night of March 14, days after Mr Tumwine's accusation, however, Wine said, "We're tired, hungry, angry and oppressed, but we still have brains and are non-violent. We chose not to use violence and we are innocent. They cannot outnumber us." 

"I ask you to demonstrate peacefully," the NUP leader told his supporters. He has accused some judges of the Supreme Court of being biased. During a meeting with an EU team, the Ugandan politician rejected a proposal for talks with President Museveni. Wambua was last seen on Friday morning when her husband dropped her at work. President Magufuli has not appeared in public for over two weeks now. Police say they are monitoring the condition of the children before settling on the proper charge.